Nothing.

613
00:37:54,946 --> 00:37:59,493
Only a year,
and sh-she's forgotten.

614
00:38:01,328 --> 00:38:02,537
Okay, look, look, what...

615
00:38:02,579 --> 00:38:06,082
what does that have to do
with Adam?

616
00:38:06,583 --> 00:38:09,419
Oh, well, let-let's ask him.

617
00:38:10,003 --> 00:38:11,087
[Adam]
What?

618
00:38:11,171 --> 00:38:14,049
[Elizabeth] Did you leave
a note for your mom

619
00:38:14,090 --> 00:38:15,759
at the grave on the anniversary?

620
00:38:15,801 --> 00:38:18,011
[Adam]
Uh, yeah. A...

621
00:38:18,053 --> 00:38:19,095
a card.

622
00:38:19,137 --> 00:38:23,308
Uh, did you write it
or did your father?

623
00:38:23,350 --> 00:38:25,727
Me. Why?

624
00:38:25,811 --> 00:38:27,896
What'd you write?

625
00:38:27,979 --> 00:38:30,857
"I love you and always will."

626
00:38:30,941 --> 00:38:33,151
And you left it there for her?

627
00:38:33,193 --> 00:38:35,654
[Adam]
Yeah.

628
00:38:40,242 --> 00:38:42,285
ominous music

629
00:38:59,052 --> 00:39:01,012
[crickets chirping]

630
00:39:01,054 --> 00:39:03,515
[indistinct chatter]

631
00:39:13,191 --> 00:39:14,985
The soup's cold.

632
00:39:15,735 --> 00:39:17,904
It's gazpacho.

633
00:39:18,572 --> 00:39:22,534
I don't care what it's called.
It's cold.

634
00:39:24,327 --> 00:39:27,873
You want me to heat up
your gazpacho?

635
00:39:53,815 --> 00:39:56,192
[quiet laughing]

636
00:39:56,234 --> 00:39:57,402
Why does she believe you

637
00:39:57,485 --> 00:39:59,529
when you pretend you don't know
what gazpacho is?

638
00:39:59,571 --> 00:40:02,782
My Scottish tenement childhood.

639
00:40:02,866 --> 00:40:03,909
[Jimmy laughs]

640
00:40:03,992 --> 00:40:07,579
Porridge with salt, haggis,
neeps and tatties,

641
00:40:07,621 --> 00:40:09,122
ketchup with everything.

642
00:40:09,205 --> 00:40:11,374
I have come a very long way
to, uh...

643
00:40:11,416 --> 00:40:13,919
soup with ice in it.

644
00:40:19,466 --> 00:40:21,343
Your mother wanted me
to talk to you.

645
00:40:21,426 --> 00:40:24,763
Dad, I got to tell you,
that's a pretty weak opening.

646
00:40:24,846 --> 00:40:26,097
What?

647
00:40:26,139 --> 00:40:28,141
Confessing to being
only the messenger.

648
00:40:28,224 --> 00:40:30,435
Your confirmation. Mom says...

649
00:40:30,477 --> 00:40:32,103
There you go again.

650
00:40:33,605 --> 00:40:36,942
Why not just decide to believe?

651
00:40:36,983 --> 00:40:38,151
Believe in God,

652
00:40:38,234 --> 00:40:40,070
the all-powerful,
narcissistic cynic?

653
00:40:40,153 --> 00:40:42,364
I'm not even sure
I like him, Dad.

654
00:40:42,447 --> 00:40:45,241
-Fia, ca--
-Dad, what do you want me to do?

655
00:40:45,283 --> 00:40:48,662
This god, who knows everything
and decides everything

656
00:40:48,703 --> 00:40:50,622
and a week ago woke up
and thought, "Oh, I know,

657
00:40:50,705 --> 00:40:52,290
let's kill a 17-year-old boy
in New Orleans

658
00:40:52,374 --> 00:40:54,626
just for the hell of it"--
I have to love him?

659
00:40:54,709 --> 00:40:57,045
Don't-don't-don't
do this to her.

660
00:40:57,087 --> 00:40:58,254
-Not now.
-Do you love him?

661
00:40:58,338 --> 00:40:59,589
-It's not the right time.
-Dad, I'm jus...

662
00:40:59,631 --> 00:41:04,135
Just do what I fucking say!

663
00:41:23,405 --> 00:41:25,407
I'm, like, trying to get
a little bit more specific

664
00:41:25,490 --> 00:41:28,451
on the girl
and who and when and wh...

665
00:41:28,535 --> 00:41:29,661
When-when was it?

666
00:41:29,703 --> 00:41:31,871
-Eighth grade.
-Eighth grade?

667
00:41:31,955 --> 00:41:34,499
Eighth grade.
Jennifer St. George.

668
00:41:34,582 --> 00:41:36,626
Oh, my God. Jennifer.

669
00:41:36,710 --> 00:41:38,670
-Mm.
-[chuckles] She was--

670
00:41:38,753 --> 00:41:41,089
-Worth fighting for.
-First and only fight.

671
00:41:41,172 --> 00:41:43,216
-[Nancy] Mm.
-Who won?

672
00:41:43,258 --> 00:41:45,051
-Who do you think?
-Who do you think?

673
00:41:45,093 --> 00:41:46,594
-My money's here.
-[Michael] No.

674
00:41:46,678 --> 00:41:49,014
Sorry, Judge.

675
00:41:50,140 --> 00:41:51,725
Red? White?

676
00:41:51,808 --> 00:41:54,185
-Bourbon.
-[laughter]

677
00:41:54,227 --> 00:41:57,439
Did I ever tell you
how much I love you?

678
00:41:57,522 --> 00:41:58,690
-Mmm!
-No, Charlie...

679
00:41:58,773 --> 00:42:00,400
Wh... Get your
sticky hands off me!

680
00:42:00,483 --> 00:42:02,694
-And get me some bourbon.
-[chuckles]

681
00:42:02,777 --> 00:42:04,154
-[doorbell rings]
-[Charlie] You want ice?

682
00:42:04,195 --> 00:42:06,406
[Elizabeth]
No i... No, no. No ice.

683
00:42:06,489 --> 00:42:09,367
Okay. No, I got-I got it.

684
00:42:10,577 --> 00:42:12,078
-Hey.
-Hey.

685
00:42:12,162 --> 00:42:13,329
I've been trying to call you.

686
00:42:13,371 --> 00:42:15,373
I-I didn't mean to disturb you.

687
00:42:15,415 --> 00:42:16,708
[Nancy] I have the DVDs.
You probably don't even know

688
00:42:16,791 --> 00:42:18,626
-what that is, either.
-A DVD?

689
00:42:18,668 --> 00:42:19,961
-[laughs]
-Can you explain that one?

690
00:42:20,045 --> 00:42:21,379
We used to put things
in a machine...

691
00:42:21,463 --> 00:42:25,300
-[laughing]
-VHS. Oh, my gosh.

692
00:42:25,383 --> 00:42:26,676
Lee Delamere.

693
00:42:26,760 --> 00:42:29,345
What you doing hanging out here
like a Jehovah's Witness?

694
00:42:29,387 --> 00:42:31,765
Get in here before
the Neighborhood Watch

695
00:42:31,806 --> 00:42:33,516
shoots your Creole ass.

696
00:42:33,558 --> 00:42:36,061
[crickets chirping]

697
00:42:36,770 --> 00:42:38,480
[whispers]
Oh, Christ.

698
00:42:38,563 --> 00:42:40,440
-Come right on in.
-Everything's delicious.

699
00:42:40,523 --> 00:42:41,608
[chuckles]

700
00:42:41,649 --> 00:42:43,777
-Mm!
-I-I don't want to intrude.

701
00:42:43,818 --> 00:42:45,487
Let's, uh,
we'll sit you right here.

702
00:42:45,528 --> 00:42:47,906
-Hi.
-Hi.

703
00:42:47,947 --> 00:42:49,074
Hi.

704
00:42:49,574 --> 00:42:51,951
[Elizabeth]
I-I don't believe we've met.

705
00:42:52,035 --> 00:42:53,453
Uh, Lee Delamere.

706
00:42:53,536 --> 00:42:54,662
-Oh, uh...
-[Lee] Yeah.

707
00:42:54,704 --> 00:42:57,248
Elizabeth is
my mother-in-law. Here.

708
00:42:57,791 --> 00:42:59,584
Uh, I-I didn't want

709
00:42:59,626 --> 00:43:02,253
-to interrupt a family dinner.
-[Elizabeth] Well,

710
00:43:02,295 --> 00:43:04,631
here you are, so... sit.

711
00:43:04,672 --> 00:43:07,842
-Please.
-Adam was discussing his future.

712
00:43:07,884 --> 00:43:10,178
[Lee]
Well, that's... that's great.

713
00:43:10,220 --> 00:43:12,430
Um... any ideas?

714
00:43:12,472 --> 00:43:15,517
Yeah. Uh, my mom
was a photographer.

715
00:43:15,600 --> 00:43:17,852
So I think I'd like to try it.

716
00:43:17,936 --> 00:43:21,272
I'd love to see
some of your work.

717
00:43:22,148 --> 00:43:23,942
Sure.

718
00:43:24,359 --> 00:43:26,569
-Hi. Hi.
-Oh. Nancy.

719
00:43:26,653 --> 00:43:28,404
Nice to meet you.
Michael forgot his manners.

720
00:43:28,488 --> 00:43:29,656
-[Nancy laughs]
-Yeah, sorry.

721
00:43:29,739 --> 00:43:31,241
No, in case
you change your mind.

722
00:43:31,324 --> 00:43:32,992
[Nancy] Oh, it's so delicious.
You really should have some.

723
00:43:33,034 --> 00:43:34,410
-I'll get you some wine, huh?
-It looks amazing.

724
00:43:34,494 --> 00:43:36,955
It smells amazing.

725
00:43:37,956 --> 00:43:41,960
-You should try the sausage.
-[laughing]

726
00:43:45,964 --> 00:43:46,673
Oh.

727
00:43:46,756 --> 00:43:50,301
Some of these,
actually, are Mom's.

728
00:43:51,261 --> 00:43:52,595
Let me see those.

729
00:43:52,679 --> 00:43:53,555
[mumbles]

730
00:43:53,638 --> 00:43:55,181
Thank you, honey.

731
00:43:55,265 --> 00:43:57,475
-Thank you.
-Well,

732
00:43:57,559 --> 00:43:59,435
I've never seen these.

733
00:43:59,519 --> 00:44:02,438
Uh, they were in Mom's Leica.

734
00:44:03,189 --> 00:44:05,483
So her last photographs.

735
00:44:06,359 --> 00:44:08,820
God, she was good.

736
00:44:09,362 --> 00:44:10,905
Have you seen these?

737
00:44:10,947 --> 00:44:13,491
Uh, no.

738
00:44:16,286 --> 00:44:18,496
[Nancy]
May I?

739
00:44:18,538 --> 00:44:20,707
Oh. Yeah. Of course.

740
00:44:21,416 --> 00:44:22,792
Yeah, pass those over.

741
00:44:22,876 --> 00:44:25,128
Don't get your...

742
00:44:27,755 --> 00:44:30,383
Oh, I remember you now.

743
00:44:30,425 --> 00:44:32,594
Yeah, yeah, the intern.

744
00:44:32,677 --> 00:44:34,637
[Lee exhales]

745
00:44:34,679 --> 00:44:36,556
Long time ago.
[chuckles]

746
00:44:36,639 --> 00:44:38,516
But now here you are.

747
00:44:40,977 --> 00:44:44,981
Just, uh, wanted to pick
Michael's brain about a case.

748
00:44:45,523 --> 00:44:47,567
At night at home?

749
00:44:47,609 --> 00:44:50,361
Some things can't wait.

750
00:44:51,237 --> 00:44:52,405
Go ahead.

751
00:44:57,493 --> 00:44:59,037
Okay.

752
00:45:01,331 --> 00:45:04,751
A kid I was representing...

753
00:45:04,834 --> 00:45:07,462
well, he died in OPP.

754
00:45:07,545 --> 00:45:08,755
Actually, he was murdered,

755
00:45:08,796 --> 00:45:12,383
uh, after being tortured
by the NOPD.

756
00:45:12,467 --> 00:45:15,553
[Elizabeth]
That's a big word.

757
00:45:15,595 --> 00:45:17,889
Is that the right word?

758
00:45:19,599 --> 00:45:21,935
Michael?

759
00:45:22,018 --> 00:45:23,978
Um...

760
00:45:24,020 --> 00:45:27,523
Yes, it-it... it looks that way.

761
00:45:30,693 --> 00:45:32,237
[Lee]
The world is working very hard

762
00:45:32,320 --> 00:45:36,866
to describe this child's death
as something of no interest.

763
00:45:36,908 --> 00:45:38,910
Him as someone of no value.

764
00:45:38,993 --> 00:45:44,040
But the world's doing that
because it's frightened.

765
00:45:44,791 --> 00:45:47,543
I can smell the fear.

766
00:45:47,627 --> 00:45:49,837
That's a good thing,
'cause I can work on fear.

767
00:45:49,921 --> 00:45:53,049
And with a little help
from our friends...

768
00:45:54,217 --> 00:45:57,220
When did you start
calling him Michael?

769
00:45:58,846 --> 00:46:00,890
Recently.

770
00:46:00,932 --> 00:46:03,643
-What kind of torture?
-Adam.

771
00:46:03,726 --> 00:46:06,312
I don't think we should be
talking about him like this.

772
00:46:06,396 --> 00:46:07,522
[Lee]
Really?

773
00:46:07,563 --> 00:46:10,650
We've done 400 years
of not talking.

774
00:46:10,692 --> 00:46:14,112
Kind of in favor
of getting it out there.

775
00:46:15,655 --> 00:46:18,616
[Adam]
What'd they do to him?

776
00:46:22,745 --> 00:46:25,581
CS gas pumped through a hose

777
00:46:25,665 --> 00:46:26,833
into a locked vehicle

778
00:46:26,916 --> 00:46:29,210
with him hog-tied inside.

779
00:46:29,252 --> 00:46:31,796
[Elizabeth]
What did this young man do?

780
00:46:31,879 --> 00:46:33,965
What, to get tortured?

781
00:46:34,007 --> 00:46:36,676
-To get arrested.
-[Django whining]

782
00:46:36,759 --> 00:46:37,802
-[barks]
-[Michael] Django.

783
00:46:37,885 --> 00:46:39,304
[whining]

784
00:46:39,345 --> 00:46:40,513
He stole a car.

785
00:46:40,555 --> 00:46:42,348
-Django!
-Mom's car.

786
00:46:42,432 --> 00:46:44,475
Wait, you knew about this?

787
00:46:46,936 --> 00:46:48,146
He stole Robin's car,

788
00:46:48,187 --> 00:46:49,939
then he was tortured,
then he was murdered?

789
00:46:50,023 --> 00:46:51,774
The car was used
in a hit-and-run.

790
00:46:51,858 --> 00:46:54,527
[Elizabeth]
Well, you know what they say.

791
00:46:54,569 --> 00:46:55,945
Crime in this city.

792
00:46:56,029 --> 00:46:57,613
[Charlie]
Vote for Charlie Figaro.

793
00:46:57,655 --> 00:46:58,990
Tough on crime,

794
00:46:59,073 --> 00:47:01,075
